data.name: TrainingPlanHtml_LegendContent
data.value: MFMuscle failure. You should do as many reps as you can until you cannot do more SSSuper slow. You should perform this set very slow. RPRest pause. You should perform this set as soon as you don't feel muscle pain (after 10 sec). MAXYou should do as many reps as you can do correctly WVery light warm up set. AMAlmost max. You should do almost maximum reps (max-1 for example) XYou should do X reps (for example 10) and finish this set. -XYou should do maximum X reps and finish this set. For example -10 means that you should do maximum 10 reps (or less) X-You should do minimum X reps. For example 10- means that you should do minimum 10 reps (or more). X-YYou should do minimum X and maximum Y reps. You finish the current set when you reach the maximum number or you don't have strength to do more. For example 10-12 means that you should do minimum 10 and maximum 12 reps. ^ZDrop set. Z means how many drops we have, for example ^2 means that for this set you will have 2 additional drops of weight 8-10^1This value means that you do minimum 8 and maximum 10 reps. After this you drop some weight (drop set) and you do next repetitions.

data.name: usrExerciseEditor_MetHelp
data.value:
The ratio of the work metabolic rate to the resting metabolic rate. One MET is defined as 1 kcal/kg/hour and is roughly equivalent to the energy cost of sitting quietly. It is used to calculate burned calories for cardio exercises. For most weight exercises you should use value 5 for MET.
Click the link to see a list of exercises with MET value.
